:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aimery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Kemery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kemery","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived in the Middle Ages from a personal name introduced to England by the Normans. This was originally composed of the Germanic elements <i>amal</i> ‘bravery, vigour’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’, but soon assumed a variety of forms such as <i>Amauri</i> and <i>Emauri</i>."]}]},{"name":"VI","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aimery VI De Thouars was born in 1095, in Anjou, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, France, his father, Aimery de Thouars V, was 51 and his mother, Agnès ?, was 41. He married Agnes of Aquitaine, wife of Ramiro II of Aragon, Queen consort of Aragon House of Poitiers on 11 April 1116. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. In 1182, his occupation is listed as 15ème vicomte de thouars de 1182 à 1225. He died in 1127, in Thouars, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1095–1127, killed in battle":"1095–1127","1095–1127":"1095–1127","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1103–1159":"1103–1159","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1120–1173":"1120–1173","1128–Female":"1128–Surnud","1045–1089":"1045–1089","1055–1123":"1055–1123","11 April 1116":"11. aprill 1116","1055":"1055","1120":"1120","1173":"1173","1095":"1095","1128":"1128","1127":"1127","ABT 1120":"umbes 1120","1159":"1159","1125":"1125","1103":"1103","1123":"1123","1089":"1089","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1127, killed in battle":"1127","after 1123":"pärast 1123","Thouars,79329,Deux-Sèvres,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Thouars, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Thouars, Deux-Sevres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Thouars, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Anjou, Isere, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Anjou, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1095–1127, killed in battle":"1095–1127","1095–1127":"1095–1127","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1103–1159":"1103–1159","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","1120–1173":"1120–1173","1128–Female":"1128–Kuollut","1045–1089":"1045–1089","1055–1123":"1055–1123","11 April 1116":"11. huhtikuuta 1116","1055":"1055","1120":"1120","1173":"1173","1095":"1095","1128":"11